1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,220
So far, we have been looking into how to create a large language model from scratch.

2

00:00:05,220  -->  00:00:07,660
Now, let's look into how to use

3

00:00:07,660  -->  00:00:10,820
existing large language models and how to

4

00:00:10,820  -->  00:00:14,480
adapt them to various tasks in your applications.

5

00:00:14,480  -->  00:00:19,860
While it is important to understand how large language models work under the hood,

6

00:00:19,860  -->  00:00:25,360
it is unlikely you will need to create one from scratch for your applications.

7

00:00:25,360  -->  00:00:28,680
Training an LLM from scratch is challenging,

8

00:00:28,680  -->  00:00:31,355
and there are a few reasons for this.

9

00:00:31,355  -->  00:00:34,670
Training these models require huge amounts of

10

00:00:34,670  -->  00:00:38,630
training data and a lot of computational resources.

11

00:00:38,630  -->  00:00:42,310
These models are also very expensive to train.

12

00:00:42,310  -->  00:00:49,045
For example, the cost of training GPT-4 model cost more than $100 million.

13

00:00:49,045  -->  00:00:54,240
Finally, developing new models require a specialized skill set,

14

00:00:54,240  -->  00:00:58,600
especially if you aim to implement a state of the art model.

15

00:00:58,600  -->  00:01:01,960
Fortunately, instead of creating a model from scratch,

16

00:01:01,960  -->  00:01:04,700
we can use existing models created by

17

00:01:04,700  -->  00:01:08,740
companies and researchers from all around the world.

18

00:01:08,740  -->  00:01:13,070
To do this, we will use the Hugging Face library,

19

00:01:13,070  -->  00:01:18,540
which is one of the most popular NLP libraries for Python.

20

00:01:18,540  -->  00:01:21,200
At the moment of this recording,

21

00:01:21,200  -->  00:01:27,810
it has a whopping 127,000 stars on GitHub.

22

00:01:27,810  -->  00:01:32,950
It also has a huge community contributing to the project,

23

00:01:32,950  -->  00:01:38,240
developing new large language models and improving its features.

24

00:01:38,240  -->  00:01:43,030
Hugging Face simplifies building applications using LLMs,

25

00:01:43,030  -->  00:01:45,110
but it's not limited to this.

26

00:01:45,110  -->  00:01:49,830
It also provides tools for developing new LLMs, as well.

27

00:01:49,830  -->  00:01:55,870
Hugging Face is a collection of multiple components that all work together.

28

00:01:55,870  -->  00:02:02,030
It provides an API that allows us to build applications using LLMs.

29

00:02:02,030  -->  00:02:04,850
We can access a large collection of

30

00:02:04,850  -->  00:02:08,810
pre-trained models that we can use in our applications.

31

00:02:08,810  -->  00:02:13,850
It also provides access to datasets for different purposes that

32

00:02:13,850  -->  00:02:18,695
we can use to train our models or improve existing models.

33

00:02:18,695  -->  00:02:22,570
Finally, it provides the spaces project that allows

34

00:02:22,570  -->  00:02:26,690
to quickly create machine learning demos and applications.

35

00:02:26,690  -->  00:02:28,495
Speaking of its API,

36

00:02:28,495  -->  00:02:30,470
Hugging Face provides a set of

37

00:02:30,470  -->  00:02:37,090
flexible and powerful APIs that we can use to build our AI applications.

38

00:02:37,090  -->  00:02:43,970
Using their API, we can do things like access existing models for a variety of tasks,

39

00:02:43,970  -->  00:02:45,935
such as text generation,

40

00:02:45,935  -->  00:02:48,970
text summarization, and so on.

41

00:02:48,970  -->  00:02:52,005
We can train new models,

42

00:02:52,005  -->  00:02:57,675
or we can fine tune existing models from their library of models.

43

00:02:57,675  -->  00:03:03,110
Fine tuning is a process that allows us to take an existing model and

44

00:03:03,110  -->  00:03:05,910
update its weights to make it better for

45

00:03:05,910  -->  00:03:09,350
a specific task for which the model wasn't trained for.

46

00:03:09,350  -->  00:03:12,170
We can also process text for LLMs.

47

00:03:12,170  -->  00:03:16,590
For example, we can tokenize a text using an existing tokenizer,

48

00:03:16,590  -->  00:03:20,410
or we can even create our own tokenizer.

49

00:03:21,110  -->  00:03:25,350
Finally, we can deploy our LLMs.

50

00:03:25,350  -->  00:03:30,415
Hugging Face is also not limited to working with just text.

51

00:03:30,415  -->  00:03:34,740
It also includes APIs to work with images and audio.

52

00:03:34,740  -->  00:03:39,330
You might be wondering how Hugging Face is different from OpenAI.

53

00:03:39,330  -->  00:03:44,300
Both provide models and allow us to build applications using them.

54

00:03:44,300  -->  00:03:48,005
These however, are very different companies.

55

00:03:48,005  -->  00:03:51,990
Hugging Face is an open source product.

56

00:03:51,990  -->  00:03:59,070
We can run models from Hugging Face locally on our laptops or on servers that we control.

57

00:03:59,070  -->  00:04:03,070
Finally, Hugging Face models are free to use.

58

00:04:03,070  -->  00:04:05,455
On the other hand, OpenAI,

59

00:04:05,455  -->  00:04:09,365
despite the name, provides closed source models.

60

00:04:09,365  -->  00:04:13,570
They only allow us to access their models via the API,

61

00:04:13,570  -->  00:04:18,590
and these models run on servers that OpenAI operates.

62

00:04:18,590  -->  00:04:24,980
Finally, we also need to pay to access advanced OpenAI models.
